Your insert returns 1 on success and 0 on failure. If you want to use the primary key, use getId() of the object you used to insert.

Example:

    // 1 or 0 = success or failure
    int result = activityLogDao.createActivityLog(alog);

    // get Id, the &#39;alog&#39; object mapped to the id
    Integer myId = alog.getId();

As `&lt;selectKey /&gt;` requires extra query, `useGeneratedKey` is preferred in general.  
I&#39;ll show you how to use `useGeneratedKeys` for the following usages.

1. Use `nextval` in insert statement
2. Use `nextval` as the default value of a column
3. Use `identity` column

For explanation, I&#39;ll use a separate table for each case.


```sql
create sequence test_seq increment by 1 start with 1;

create table user1 (
  id int,
  name varchar(10)
);

create table user2 (
  id int default test_seq.nextval,
  name varchar(10)
);

create table user3 (
  id int generated always as identity,
  name varchar(10)
);
```

Insert statement for usage 1 would look as follows.

```java
@Insert({
  &quot;insert into user1 (id, name)&quot;,
    &quot;values (test_seq.nextval, #{name})&quot;})
@Options(useGeneratedKeys = true,
  keyProperty = &quot;id&quot;, keyColumn = &quot;id&quot;)
void insert1(User user);
```

Here is an XML version just for the sake of completeness.

```xml
&lt;insert id=&quot;insert1&quot; useGeneratedKeys=&quot;true&quot;
  keyProperty=&quot;id&quot; keyColumn=&quot;id&quot;&gt;
  insert into user1 (id, name)
    values (test_seq.nextval, #{name})
&lt;/insert&gt;
```


Insert statements for usage 2 and 3 are essentially the same.  
Note that `id` is omitted from the column list.


```java
@Insert({&quot;insert into user2 (name) values (#{name})&quot;})
@Options(useGeneratedKeys = true,
  keyProperty = &quot;id&quot;, keyColumn = &quot;id&quot;)
